SUMMARY:Olio Read-in: Anne Carson's Eros the Bittersweet
DESCRIPTION:What is required of the solitary soul\, typically content withi
 n the interior known as I\, when it finds itself in a surprising and new\,
  often painful state of longing to find union with another? What are the f
 undamental physics of crossing my self-imposed border when I am desperatel
 y longing for you? Because longing\, as any longer can tell you\, is not e
 nough. While its cousin\, the Imagination\, can help by filling up our int
 erior with illusions of union\, this relief is always temporary. Even when
  bolstered by gadgets and screens\, sooner or later\, the self grows suspe
 ct of its own hacks\, and the yearning takes over. Such beautiful yearning
 .&nbsp\;To know oneself\, to know where I begin\, and to witness the eroti
 c that exists where I end. Such endeavors require more than longing. They 
 need Eros. Movement. To connect with another\, we need first and foremost\
 , action. To lift our hand out and reach across space\, to "You."Typically
  understood as a state of erotic desire\, Eros\, Anne Carson tells us is s
 omething so much more and so much less all at once. One perfect sentence i
 nstructs: "Eros is a verb."This is an invitation to you to move\, to join\
 , to take part in this special event\, an Olio Read-in.Rooted in the socia
 l revolution of the 1960s\, Read-ins have always been essential to the pol
 itical project of building communities\, and bolstering progressive change
 . Read Ins announce: We will not remain alone\, afraid\, and cut off from 
 one another. No. We will sit side by side and with the support of each oth
 er\, we will read. We will learn. We will enrich our inner world so that w
 e can find the courage to exist outside of it.Teacher: Jamie WarrenJamie W
 arren has a Ph.D. in American History from Indiana University\, and she is
  an Assistant Professor at BMCC-CUNY where she teaches American history\, 
 the history of women and gender\, and women’s studies. Her research focu
 ses on slavery in antebellum South with a particular focus on death\, the 
 body\, and the philosophy of history.Evening Flow7:30 PM – Doors open. S
 ettle in\, grab a drink\, and meet a friend.8 PM – The Olio begins: an i
 ntimate\, interactive lecture and guided exploration.9 PM – We shift int
 o a social experience\, discussing ideas with others in the room while the
  teacher joins and floats between conversations.10 PM - Last call at the b
 ar and we'll start to wind down the evening.What Is an Olio?Think Olio is 
 an ongoing experiment in lifelong learning. We are a community of open-min
 ded people who gather to exchange ideas with new friends and connect over 
 art\, literature\, and philosophy.Check out our full calendarOur $30 membe
 rship gives you two events for the price of one!&nbsp\;An Olio is what we 
 call the social learning events we’ve been organizing since 2015. A blen
 d between a lecture and a house party\, Olios are led by a teacher who lov
 es sharing their passions and the room is filled with curious\, open-minde
 d New Yorkers.&nbsp\;Our goal is to spark new perspectives\, ignite curios
 ity\, and enjoy ourselves socially—an alternative to typical nightlife o
 ptions.Disclaimer: By purchasing a ticket\, you agree to have your photo/v
 ideo used for social media/marketing materials. If you prefer to not have 
 your photo taken\, feel free to send us a note.Photo by Zhi-Da Zhong\n\nTi
 ckets & info: https://www.viewcy.com/event/olio_readin_anne_ca
URL:https://www.viewcy.com/event/olio_readin_anne_ca
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:94c958c5-1255-4dd5-baea-918024427918@viewcy.olio
